Detailed Description

This namespace contains various classes and functions défining mathematical objects and numerical algorithms.

Tensorial objects

The TFEL/Math library provides two classes for second order tensors:

  • The stensor class which describes symmetric second order tensors.
  • The tensor class which describes general second order (symmetric and unsymmetric) tensors.

Fourth order tensors are linear transformations of second order tensors.

this function checks if the given type matches the given unit if it built on top of a quantity. If the given type is built on a plain old scalar type, this function always returns true.

◆ computeDeviatorDeterminantDerivative() [1/2]

TFEL_HOST_DEVICE constexpr auto tfel::math::computeDeviatorDeterminantDerivative ( const StensorConcept auto &  s)
constexprnoexcept
Returns
the derivative of the determinant of the deviator of symmetric tensor.

Let \(\underline{s}\) be a symmetric tensor and \(J_{3}\) be the determinant of \(\underline{s}'\) the deviator of \(\underline{s}\):

\[ J_{3} = \mathrm{det}\left(\underline{s}'\right) = \mathrm{det}\left(\underline{s}-\mathrm{tr}\left(\underline{s}'\right)\,\underline{I}\right) \]

This function computes \(\displaystyle\frac{\partial J_{3}}{\partial \underline{\sigma}}\).

Parameters
[in]stensor where the the determinant is evaluated

◆ init_floating_point_exceptions()

void tfel::math::init_floating_point_exceptions ( )
inline

this function enables C99 floating point rounding and exception handling:

  • FE_DIVBYZERO: the DivideByZero exception occurs when an operation on finite numbers produces infinity as exact answer.
  • FE_UNDERFLOW: the Overflow exception occurs when a result has to be represented as a floating point number, but has (much) larger absolute value than the largest (finite) floating point number that is representable.
  • FE_OVERFLOW: the Underflow exception occurs when a result has to be represented as a floating point number, but has smaller absolute value than the smallest positive normalized floating point number (and would lose much accuracy when represented as a denormalized number).
  • FE_INEXACT: the Inexact exception occurs when the rounded result of an operation is not equal to the infinite precision result. It may occur whenever Overflow or Underflow occurs.

◆ norm() [1/3]

TFEL_HOST_DEVICE constexpr auto tfel::math::norm ( const ST2toST2Concept auto &  A)
constexprnoexcept

This function computes the norm of a st2tost2 as.

\[ ||A||=\sqrt{\frac{1}{N}{}^tA::A}\]

where

\[N\]

is the size of the tensor (for example,

\[6\]

for a dimension 3, and

\[4\]

for a dimension 2).

\[ ||A||=\sqrt{\frac{1}{N}\sum_{i,j,k,l}A_{ijkl}A_{ijkl}}\]

or also

\[ ||A||=\sqrt{\frac{1}{N}\sum_{i,j} A_{ij}A_{ij}}\]

in Voigt notation. The factor

\[\frac 1N\]

ensures that the norm of

\[I\]

is 1.

Returns
the norm
Parameters
[in]Ast2tost2

◆ VoigtIndex()

template<unsigned short N>
TFEL_HOST_DEVICE constexpr unsigned short tfel::math::VoigtIndex ( unsigned short  i,
unsigned short  j 
)
constexpr

This function returns the Voigt index of two indices (beginning from 0). Hence, the correspondence is, in 3d:

\[(0,0)->0, (1,1)->1, (2,2)->2, (0,1) or (1,0) -> 3, (0,2) or (2,0) -> 4, (1,2) or (2,1)-> 5\]

. In 2d, it is

\[(0,0)->0, (1,1)->1, (2,2)->2, (0,1) or (1,0) -> 3\]

. In 1d,

\[(0,0)->0, (1,1)->1, (2,2)->2\]

. Be careful to the Voigt indices between 3 and 5, which are different from the usual convention:

\[\varepsilon_{12}\]

is usually the last component of the vector

\[\varepsilon\]

in the usual Voigt notation, but here it is situated as the fourth component, in order that the vector in dimension 2 is just a truncation of the vector in dimension 3.

Returns
an unsigned short
Parameters
[in]i,junsigned short
